text:
‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê well marketed and quite a canny move for faber in general - anything but pale and stuffy. and on trend: there's a glut of confessional bme and feminist memoirs of sorts, along with a vogue for the arresting, defiant, first person title (all those 'this is going to hurt', 'stay in your lane', and that godawful obnoxious, bad-us-import-inflected 'why i'm no longer talking to white people [apart from my trustie chums in hackney i met at prep school]. the kitten on the cover is instant catnip too. 
i picked it up having little idea what to expect, but assumed 'essays' of sorts. perhaps one on jane austen and one on #metoo and something on bereavement maybe. these are really just chapters of a memoir though. which is fine. 
they're readable, pacy and sometimes 'funny' (in that 'book funny' kind of funny) and it's hard not to like and admire irby for the sheer honestly and directness of how she talks about her body, diet, tv, bowels, sex... admirable at times.  her experience growing up (varieties of neglect) also merits telling - the odds were pretty stacked against her. at times, it's definitely funny, in the way any self-confessed slob having to deal with the public (working at an animal hospital) generates humour. i did actually el oh el on one occasion, when she was talking food (she's good on contemporary pieties like healthy eating, etc); she describes being so ravenous for fast food as to want to rub a burger into her tits - bang. think of this as charismatic stand up. 
at other times, you're yearning for a few bracing observations on jane austen or #metoo, as it's all pretty chatty and lightweight. still, good voice and obvious comic talent.

text: it‚Äôs been just over a year since i published an article that publicly brought #metoo to roller derby (archived link in bio). since then, i‚Äôve learned a lot about what it takes to come forward with your story‚Ä¶ and in my case, the stories of others. three of the nine folks involved in the @derbycentral article were willing to put themselves out there publicly; the others were too scared of what might happen to them if their stories became known. i had nothing to lose: i was retiring and could retreat from the community; others didn‚Äôt have this luxury. and then, once the story dropped, i noticed immediately that unlike many others who have come forward about powerful men, i was overwhelmingly believed. it was instantly obvious that as a cis white lady on a world champion team, i had societal and community clout that isn‚Äôt afforded to everyone. i‚Äôve witnessed this play out time and time again since that day: folks who lack the same standing i had have been shut down or swept aside. i‚Äôm glad my article had the impact it did: it was the catalyst for public dialogue in the community, which resulted in stories being told and folks being expelled from leagues all over the world. many changes have been made on a team, league and even organizational level within @wftda, but given how many stories i still hear about predators being allowed to stay on as skaters, officials and staff, the folks in derby still have a lot of work to do. i sure as shit know i do.

text_retweet:
we need to talk
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
surviving sexual assault doesn't come with an end date. it's an ugly scar that never fully heals. and it's a part of who i am
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
last week when i woke up to see my inbox full of sexually explicit messages, i felt 17 again. scared, small and out of control
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
a plus size porn adjacent account had combed through my photos and reposted them; tagging them to me, using my image without my permission. photos that once spoke to body positivity and inclusive fashion, reduced to hyper sexualizing my body. nearly 100 comments found below objectifying my body, demeaning me and a handful that crawled from the comment section into my inbox
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i have thought long and hard about whether or not to share this. or to tell you how frequently i delete comments on my posts that make my blood boil. because a part of me, wants to hide this vulnerabilty, this trauma i haven't been able to shake for a decade
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
but instead i am choosing to share this with you, so if you're feeling alone you know you're not. to share this wound and reality with everyone of you who also feels that phantom pain of the worst moments of your life. to say there are days i struggle and if you are to, you're not alone

strength in solidarity, in just getting out of bed, in every breath we take trying to move forward - i see you
.
.
.
.

text:
trigger warning: strong, emotional, real content regarding sexual abuse. 
here's to the #metoo movement. but most of all, here's to all of the metoo-ers before it was cool. here's to the strong men and women who have lived a lifetime with that monkey on their back. here's to the kids who were too young to know what was happening. here's to the ones who compartmentalized and forgot their trauma. here's to the ones who blamed themselves instead of the monster. here's to the ones who turned to horrible addictions just to forget. here's to the ones who turned to suicide when it was their perpetrator whose life should have been taken, rest in peace, with no more pain. here's to the ones whose heads were held down, whose hands were bound, whose legs were pushed apart. here's to the ones strong enough to yell, kick, fight. or the ones who were rendered speachless, immobilized by fear and pain. why? why now, after years of sexual abuse, molestation, rape, do we have me too? why is it me "too." why can't it be "me," my story, my words, my pain? although victims should  band together for support, for understanding. i wonder, how do the demons feel strong enough to stand alone, straight, proud, indignant? ah it's because they don't have to fight every day of their life. here's to #me. and to all of the me's who are out there. whether you are strong enough to look your perpetrator in the eye, scared enough to never want see them again, cringe when you hear their name, try to forget the trauma  on a daily basis. if you are alive, if you have lived through the hell and made it out, you are the hero. even if no one knows, if you're too afraid to tell anyone. if you can make it through each day, you have won! you have won over evil, despicable, vile humans. let your life be a warning to them, "i am here, you have not succeeded.
sincerely,
me

text: hey all, i‚Äôm lauren üôãüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è when i was 15 years old, i was sexually assaulted for the very first time. i became a victim at the hands of someone whom i loved and trusted very much - a youth leader in my church. over a year and a half ago, i posted my story publicly for the first time! this act would prove to be the most difficult, yet rewarding experience of my life. while going public with my story was incredibly challenging - it also brought me a sense of healing and purpose that i had not known before. i learned that others understand what i‚Äôve been through. i am never alone in my darkness. and that vulnerability truly can set us freeüíñ so - i wanted to try to create a safe space for others who may be in the same place as me. i believe that vulnerability and openness can allow us to heal in ways we‚Äôve never imagined would be possible. let‚Äôs walk in light, rather than darkness, and lean on each other to bring hope and healing!

this allows the blame to be passed along and allows the perpetrator to dissociate and disconnect from their victims and the crime they are committing.

the burden ultimately lies on the order followers and not the order givers.

those that carry out acts, that their conscience tells them is wrong, are 100% responsible.

order followers are submitting themselves to slavery and giving up their autonomy of free will and conscious thought thus perpetuating the system of slavery and repression.

think for yourself.

pick a side.

text:
"don't cry... it was your own fault after all"
.
.
.
something i did for @kamidea s project #healgrowandblossom 
there are a lot of brave people out there who already talked about their problems. 
let me tell you my story. in 2017 i got into a very toxic and abusive relationship, mentally and physical.  it started with basic things like jealousy and soon got to the point, where he tried to control bigger parts of my life. who i was allowed to meet, to talk to or just to message. he started reading my messages and took all my privacy away from me. with everything i did i had to be afraid, that it would trigger him and knock off another fight. why i didn't break up sooner? cause he gave me the feeling that i wasn't worth to be loved by anyone else ever again. he told me this over and over again - that i wouldn't find anyone who could love me like he does. 
when i finally got away from him my perception of a normal relationship was completely shifted. it felt weird to me to have my freedom back. and it was a long way to regain parts of my self-esteem. i still sometimes doubt myself in many things and i'm afraid to get back into relationships. the worst part is that you never think that something like this could happen to you - that you are stronger than this. so the blame for yourself stays. 
but i'm trying my best to become confident with myself again and to open up to people.

also i wanna say that no matter who you are - i have an open ear for you. it can really help to just talk things off your chest!
.
.
.
.
.
.

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
‚Ä¢ my dad leaving ‚Ä¢ my parent‚Äôs getting a divorce
‚Ä¢ eating disorder
‚Ä¢ toxic relationships

text:
this one isn't for your reading pleasure. this one is meant to make you uncomfortable. as uncomfortable as it made me writing it and of course living it. i hope it makes you say "how can i be part of the solution and fast! " :
:
: "if you are a sexual assault survivor and have never sought help, please do. begin by owning your story to yourself first. you can't change it and it didn't happen because you are so and so...instead because evil happens to exist in the world we live in. we have the power to fight it and the fight starts with acceptance of the past. then, ask for help. you will be surprised how the universe alters things in your favor when you let your quests be known. help may come to you in a form of a book, a friend, a therapist, a partner, a quote. trust it and see where it takes you. it may not be a glorified one-step solution and probably won't but trust me, every attempt will get you closer to your healing, even the setbacks. " :

text:
2/3
everything was too good to be true. we rode our horses through streams and brooks. as we did so, a splash of water would hit our feet, and sprinkle on our faces so as to refresh us again and again. we rattled over bridges that straddled glacier fed streams.
the beauty that we saw, was seeping into us. 
we reached our destination, where there were lots of people in different stalls, selling different things. we jumped off to climb a little more to the glacier. 
as we walked, i noticed something. i felt like someone has started following us. however, i was a little uncertain. so, one of the friends decided that we would sit and then go, just to be sure. all agreed and we did so. 
there were four middle aged men who were following us.
‚Ä¢

text:
1/3
we went on a trek that day, 16 girls and 14 guys. four girls (including me) decided to ride a horse so that we don‚Äôt have to hike all by ourselves up to the glacier. as always, i chose the one who was the tallest and fittest of all. 
i asked the owner of my horse ‚Äúwhat is its name?‚Äù
‚Äúbadal‚Äù, he said. 
we started our journey full of excitement. as we went on, we saw beautiful landscapes enveloped by mountains with licks of grey, mauve and gold.
i slowed my horse down and i closed my eyes. i felt the cold breeze touching my skin. there was a distinct magic in the air that seemed to take away our fatigue and stress. the sudden freshness was unmissable! 
i felt like i literally am riding a cloud, it‚Äôs floating in the sky and taking me to paradise. i saw people and animals drinking from the same river and eating the same fruits. i saw goats, yaks and sheep coloured as the rocks were. grey sky having light entering through silver linings, trunks of trees as if coloured in white and music was created from laughter, chirping of birds, and the crisp leaves when the breeze would pass by them. rushing rivers, that fielded the reflection of of distant snow covered peaks. 
i felt purified and at peace.
‚Ä¢

text:
i understand this isn't the best way to start off black history month, but i keep seeing things that are making me upset at my people:

video 1 - people are hating on children! i have seen comments such as, ‚Äúif they're not black then i don't like it‚Äù or ‚Äúeveryone wanna be black but not take the struggle‚Äù. they even called children culture vultures. however, the comment that really made me upset was, ‚Äúwhen we do it everyone hates us, but when they do it they get an a‚Äù. they were covering tlc! they had the clothes and the dances. the songs were audio of tlc so what exactly they taking? music is universal! everyone would be upset black artists weren't given world tours because they're black, but you don't get world to tours without having fans who are in those countries. when you sing to a sam smith song, you're not stealing white culture or flipping gay culture. you're just singing a song because you like that song. i see way too often that if black people like kpop or anime then they're automatically shut with ‚Äúyou just like asian guys/girls.‚Äù ‚Äúyou wanna be asian now?‚Äù as if we can't step so outside the norm of what a black person is ‚Äúsupposed‚Äù to be then are only validation is for some fetish. black people have been so brainwashed to just be one thing that they force themselves to hate on others who step outside of what is deemed the proper way to be for them. then there are people who say that black is the world and how black people were the first people. yes, that has been proven; however, using it as a way to call out appropriation only discredits your argument! wouldn't that mean people have the right to do everything black? use common sense before attacking someone on their media preferences.

text:
part. 2
"mama, that time i came home for a visit,
do you remember you asked me how life was in cape town?
i lied, mama.
i said life was good, smiling,
but inside i was breaking.
my heart was torn into pieces,
for your sake, i had to put on this mask.
mama, i was scared to tell you that my body was exhausted.
from being used daily in the city as a sex slave.
mama, i wanted to tell you i was trafficked.
i was kept against my will. i was a prisoner, a sex slave.
mama, i was scared because when i‚Äôm with you i have to choose the ‚Äòright‚Äô
words.
your ears can only hear what is ‚Äògood‚Äô news.
but whom will i ever share this pain with, if i can‚Äôt share it with you?
mama, why did it take you thirty years to report dad to the police?
why did you allow him to treat you with no respect?
why did you allow him to hurt us too?" - lerato lehlebathe, cape town

text:
video 2 - a quick story on why i just can't see hair the same as most black people: i was in 7th grade and we had a sub for my english class. her grandpa had been someone who worked with dr.king and marched with him and she basically grew up around civil rights. she was talking about how white people turned on white people. my friend was sitting next to me. she was white. her hair is naturally curly and coarse. the sub asked her what race both her parents were. she said they were both white. the sub said that in those times, my friend would have not been accepted by the whites simply because her hair. i laughed at that. not because i found it funny, but because i found it idiotic. that's why i hate when people say someone isn't appreciating being black because they straighten their hair or put in weave. though i wish more of us would go natural and not follow eurocentric ideals of beauty, i also understand that black hair is so delicate and beautiful that it takes time(and quite frankly lots of money) to take care of it. but that doesn't mean someone of other race can't see the delicate beauty of black hair and take care of it with respect. especially if the hair they had previously was not doing them any justice(no offense to the guy in the video). just because his hair changes does not mean he deleted his heritage. it does not mean he is trying to be black. it does not mean he wants to take black culture. it does not mean he wants to appropriate! the same way if someone black gets a silk press or some bundles, they do not disown their blackness. that does not mean they are appropriating a non-black culture. 
i do know appropriation is real. the kardashians have taken style from other cultures and made it seem as though it is their own idea or style. i do understand that in many parts of asia there is ‚Äúhip hop style‚Äù where it seems our hair and culture is only deemed a music trend. those examples are when we should call out appropriation. but using the logic that people are using nowadays; rethink that tattoo with the asian characters. don't even think about getting some fried rice at that chinese place. you can't even listen to jhene aiko anymore.

-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.

text:
health
i feel like its something we so take for granted until it's not there. 
at least that was the case for me.
-
a long story short, last year i ended up in the emergency room with three anaphylactic reactions.  at this point we are still trying to figure out what those reactions were too and i'll be honest it's kind of scary. - 
currently i am on a wheat free diet and testing out a few theories with some great drs. (so if you have some great recipes- send them my way)
-
i share all of this, not to have y'all feel bad for me but show that even though the pictures are pretty or the family looks a certain way, we are all feeling dealing with our own stuff. stuff that sometimes is private but other times is great to share. -
this last weekend showed me just how important it is to be open and honest a.bit life's struggles bc we really are never the only ones -
so of you are struggling with health stuff - i see you, i get that it can be frustrating & it's ok to be frustrated, and i'm praying for you! üñ§üñ§
.
.
.

beginner's mind, that hopeful, ‚ù§Ô∏èchild-like perspective reminds you that everyday a journey lies before you beckoning you into the great unknown. seems like an exciting adventure, but really, who wants to always deal with the unknown? talk about terrifying.

at first glance, the security of knowing exactly who you are and where you are going offers the illusion of peace, but in many ways this mindset creates more attachment which leads to increased suffering. more suffering equals less happiness.

plan your day and be brave enough to leave at least a small opening for possibility and the unexpected miracles you will most definitely encounter. ‚ù§Ô∏è have compassion for all.. compassion makes unconditional love possible. it subtracts the need for duality which causes us to lump people and events into those elusive, yet fatal, good versus bad compartments. these types of limiting definitions close down the heart and mind and lead to isolation and loneliness.

always remember this mantra, "i am doing the very best i can and so is everybody else." this will help release you from holding yourself and others to unrealistic expectations.

bridge the gap between "yoga" happy and "real life" happy by remembering that true joy does not depend solely on external circumstances. this includes not placing too much emphasis on perfect execution of your asana, giving yourself permission to "feel" your feelings without judgment, and taking time to continuously get to know yourself everyday. .
.

please read üëâdowned cow: the true story of one anonymous animal born into the meat industry
the truck carrying this cow was unloaded one september morning. after the other animals were removed from the truck, she was left behind, unable to move. the stockyard workers used their customary electric prods in her ear to try to get her to move, then beat and kicked her in the face, ribs, and back but still she couldn't move. they tied a rope around her neck, tied the other end to a post in the ground and drove the truck away. the cow was dragged along the floor of the truck and fell to the ground, landing with both hind legs and her pelvis broken. she remained like that until 7:30 that evening.
_
for the first three hours, she lay in the hot sun crying out. periodically, when she urinated or defecated, she used her front legs to drag herself along the gravel to a clean spot. she also tried to crawl to a shaded area but couldn't move far enough. altogether, she managed to crawl a painful 13 to 14 yards. the stockyard employees wouldn't allow her any drinking water.
_
at 4:30 p.m. three dogs were attacking the cow who was still alive. she had suffered a number of bite wounds. the stockyard workers would not euthanize her, claiming that in order to preserve the value of meat, she could not be destroyed. the butcher eventually arrived at 7:30 p.m. and shot her. her body was purchased for $307.50
_
now you know. the question is what will you do? every bite of animal products that you take involves fear, cruelty, immense suffering, pain and death. ask yourself when you can not only survive but thrive on a plant-based diet, why wouldn't you? ‚û°Ô∏èwww.vegankit.com

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested¬†earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
"we just need to keep this in the family"....
many child sex abuse survivors are suffering in silence because their families have convinced them that their abuse will reflect badly on the entire family if others find out about it so they are forced to remain silent. however, the notion that keeping quiet about being sexually abused is what's best for the family is a lie! the best thing a family can do is expose and report a predator to prevent them from harming other children!! many predators will have victimized 100s of children before they are exposed. one reason for this is the fact that when families and other adults become aware or even suspect that a child is being sexually abused, they remain quiet because they are more concerned about preserving their image, reputation, status, personal comforts and stability than protecting the child(ren). in essence, they have a greater sense of loyalty to the abuser than the victim. if you are a victim or a survivor, stand in your truth. you don't owe your family or your abuser your silence. we stand with you. we believe you. and, we certainly don't agree that child sex abuse needs to be a secret the victim has to silently carry to protect their family or their abuser! #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #superbowl

text:
trigger warning:  sexual harassment 
i‚Äôll never understand when people minimize the me too movement.  maybe they haven‚Äôt been violated, made to feel helpless, feel trapped, feel less than. 
this is me at my rawest, unfiltered, vulnerable, exposed self.  i share this so maybe it helps someone.  this past weekend was one of the best weekends for me doing what i love.  activism.  very little sleep was had over the three days.  very little food.  but the adrenalin was running aplenty. 
by the time of the march and cube sunday night, my emotions had careened along the roller coaster of life.  during outreach at the cube, i finally had time to hug and sincerely thank everyone that came to the march.  maybe he saw me doing that.  i don‚Äôt know.  my memory is a little blurred of what happened because i was so triggered.  this is what i know.  a man asked me for a hug.  he had been drinking and looked to be in a tough spot in life.  i extended a hug and kindness.  he told me he loved me so much.  it was harmless.  a couple more hugs were exchanged.  he isn‚Äôt the one.  someone else saw this opportunity and exploited it.  he asked me for a hug.  took my hand and kissed it.  mostly wordless.  he looked to be in the same life situation.  my creeper vibes kicked in.  he asked for a couple more hugs, each time staring at me weirdly.  the third time, he grabbed my boob.  purposefully.  calculated.  violated.  that‚Äôs where it gets blurry.  i froze.  panicked.  didn‚Äôt know what to do.  i‚Äôm a strong independent woman that can take care of myself.  but i couldn‚Äôt.  i don‚Äôt know what happened.  the brazenness?  in public surrounded by people, thinking i wouldn‚Äôt notice?  i walked away.  i told two ladies and two men.  he was still there.  he kept watching me.  he kept approaching me.  he freaked me the fuck out.  i warned the other ladies to stay away.  he approached me and @amanda.finstad stood in between us and got through to him.  she was strong when i couldn‚Äôt be.  she saved me.  if it wasn‚Äôt for her and @laurenschraven... my night was ruined.  this was after a man mansplained to me during my live video, condescending and self-righteous. 
cont‚Äôd below.... #metoo

------ every step i take with christ reveals more of the things that i need to surrender and the things i need to improve especially in the area of being a christian daughter to non-christian parents. the call to obey and honor them really requires grace from god. if i weren't abiding in jesus, i would break down any moment because its just too difficult and draining. if i let my emotions rule over my life, im gonna be adding more problems to the ones god is fixing. but as a believer i am so blessed because the good thing is, grace abounds in a life fully surrendered to him. he will never leave us nor forsake us. he counsels us with his perfect wisdom. he comforts us with his perfect love. he equips us in all the things he desires us to do. all of these and more, he freely gives to those who love him and follow him. ------

text:
‚ö†Ô∏è thoughtful post! 
today i encountered a very uncomfortable situation that gets me all worked up and would like to share it with you. please üôèüèΩshare your thoughts!
‚Ä¢
i was walking duke around my building this morning when a big moving truck [full of men - 7 or 8] approached the area and parked next to the sidewalk. they started to whistle, throw kisses and call me ‚Äòbabe‚Äô or ‚Äòmami‚Äô in spanish. i‚Äôm crawling out of my skin at this point, because i get to experience this every single day on my walks with duke. i replied to the man: ‚Äòdo not be disrespectful‚Äô, in a strong demanding voice. so the rest of the men somehow felt defensive and pumped up because it was a group of them üòí so they started yelling and calling me names as i walked away. names like ‚Äúangry‚Äù, ‚Äúbad tempered‚Äù and ‚Äúugly‚Äù
‚Ä¢
the idea of ‚Äòcomplimenting‚Äô someone for their ‚Äòlooks‚Äô has turned into something obscene and disgusting. the idea of someone i dont know calling me babe or mami because they feel a sense of entitlement over me, is not ok! the look in their faces is wild, vulgar and offensive. almost like a predator about to catch their prey.
we are human beings,  intellectually favored by reason. unlike animals, we have tact. learn how to use those abilities and behave like one! 
because of people like the men in that truck, humanity seems like is going to shit... but i refuse to think like that! i think we have control of it. i think we have to put on our righteous hats and spread our wisest words to talk about this! education is the way to many things, but also the way to keep our integrity high!
‚Ä¢
also, these situations may influence you into dressing differently to not call their attention, or stop walking your pet (for example) but that is not the answer... you are only adapting to the issue, not working to resolve it!

text:
why has society normalized the act of wasting your energy on reaching out to people who don‚Äôt even acknowledge your efforts? why has it become socially acceptable to be miserable, and endure immature behavior from people who aren‚Äôt worth your time, and no longer serve a fulfilling purpose in your life? why have fake smiles and empty gestures become the foundation upon which so many modern relationships are built?
you should only keep people in your life because they mean something to you; you genuinely care about them and value their presence. if they don‚Äôt feel the same about you, leave them alone. delete them on social media. delete their number. remove yourself from their orbit. don‚Äôt waste your time. stop with the polite friendships and relationships. either a person matters, or they don‚Äôt. either they care about you, or they don‚Äôt.
see, here‚Äôs the thing: communication should not be mysterious.
you should not have to wear yourself out trying to achieve communication with someone. it should not be a chore. it should not be forced. you shouldn‚Äôt have to beg for it. you shouldn‚Äôt have to spend sleepless nights talking to your bedroom ceiling, and everything beyond, asking for a text back, or some form of validation that the other person actually cares about you.
communication is not a game. you shouldn‚Äôt have to bend at awkward angles to decode it or walk on eggshells to maintain it. you also shouldn‚Äôt have to constantly initiate it. communication is a two-way street. their effort should match your effort. if their effort is nonexistent, then the truth of the matter is, so is your friendship or relationship. if you choose to stay anyway, then, unfortunately, so is your self-respect.
it‚Äôs okay to let go of who is no longer fulfilling their purpose in your happiness. it‚Äôs okay to outgrow people. it‚Äôs okay to finallychoose yourself

text:
sedna square mercury and stationed direct :: ocean lovers & sea of survivors // per usual there is a lot going on in the cosmos as it is an ever-evolving entity; however, my sights have been set on sedna since august when it went into retrograde. as of february 7, sedna is moving forward and is currently squaring mercury (communication, learning). today is as good a day as ever to talk about one of my favorite celestial bodies.
‚Äî
there are many things that make sedna a unique and powerful celestial body in our solar system:
1) classification: undecided whether it is a tno (trans-neptunian object), scattered disc, or inner oort cloud
2) name: one of the only planets in our solar system named after a non-greek or roman god or goddess...her myth is from inuit tradition. 
3) orbit: irregular orbit suggests it is being pulled out of a solar system by a possible mystery planetary body.
‚Äî
archetypally and mythologically sedna has an important story to tell as well. i often call sedna the mermaid planet and in particular, see it featured prominently in charts or by transit of ocean activists or water lovers (current examples would be @theoceancleanup @thewhaledreamer @narwhalswake ). and while sedna has similar solar system real estate has neptune and pluto, it has a different energy than watery neptune or depth provoking pluto provides.  a clear archetypal aspect and energy of sedna to me is that with so many parts of ourselves and our solar system unfamiliar to us, she represents an archetypal empowered feminine we have yet to live into and understand.  a feminine that was injured or victimized and is now calling back her power (i'm looking at you #metoo movement).
‚Äî
read about sedna's myth and other archetypal energies as well as altar item suggestions, on my blog.

#sedna #depth #unconcious #myth #tno #astrology #astronomy #retrograde #northnode #mercury #juno #anthonygalbraith üì∑ anthony galbraith (can‚Äôt find an instagram page to tag or i would)

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign‚Äôs use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people‚Äôs profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there ‚Äúcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating‚Äù. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday‚Äôs hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
#notogaggingorders #notobullying #canyouhearme #notoracism #notosexism #speakyourtruth #freedomofspeech #zerotolerance

they've made me an offer.... with a gagging order. thank you,  but no. nobody really needs to know about shit and banana skins or anything else... but ....i am a baby of the windrush. not all of our parents were able to tell their story...... about the passage here and the racism they faced. 
i am the child of a generation that experienced 'no dogs,  no irish. no blacks!' doesn't anyone want to hear our stories; about michael who didn't want any of the black secretaries working as his pa, he'd rather pick a less qualified and less experienced person? 
doesn't anyone want to hear about the other one who thinks it's amusing to call a child 'black poopoo' or music of a different culture 'monkey music.... '

i had replaced all the toilet brushes and toilet brush holders. brand new. lovely.  clean. white. would you believe that someone bought in an old heavily soiled loo brush....and when i say heavily soiled so much shit was mashed into this brush.....it had to be deliberate..... if we don't tell our story it's as if we were never here.  i've received accolades and made people money so i know i was here. i've also been used and abused.... and damaged... so i know i was definitely here.

victim support have called. i have retold what i can recall. yes. i was definitely here.

odw  8. 2.19 (c)

thank you for sharing üíï

i had replaced all the toilet brushes and toilet brush holders. brand new. lovely.  clean. white. would you believe that someone bought in an old heavily soiled loo brush....and when i say heavily soiled so much shit was mashed into this brush.....it had to be deliberate..... if we do not tell our story it is as if we were never here.  i have received accolades and made people money so i know i was here. i have also been used and abused.... and damaged... so i know i was definitely here.

victim suppo have called. i have retold what i can recall. yes. i was definitely here.

odw  8. 2.19 (c)

thank you for sharing üíï

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. he‚Äôs the only straight man i‚Äôve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

all guests are welcome to take a look around the permanent exhibition before moving to the kitchen where we‚Äôll serve up delicious searcys food plus three speakers who‚Äôll be giving their take on how much of their career, or life journey, was down to design - and how much was down to luck or judgement.

text:
@_laracappelli_ taking over for the week.
.
another portrait from expectations of growth, a project documenting a group of scottish teenagers as they approach their 16th birthday, which marks the day they gain the right to sexual consent.
.
the teenagers portrayed in the images are first ones to gain the right to sexual consent in the wake of the #metoo campaign - they are part of a new generation talking about gender norms, as well as sex and consent.
i wanted to capture the teenagers as though caught between a state of pensive adulthood and child-like vulnerability - presenting an almost illusory interpretation of the cusp that they find themselves in.
.
.
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates suppoed by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cu devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
the art of speaking without speaking
(and 1-finger-typing)
by tosh tosh

happy losar ‚Äì the saga

looks like it‚Äôs going to be a rip-roaring 'happy losar.' i can feel it in my bones, at least in the functional ones. all the contention from the words ‚Äòfemale‚Äô and ‚Äòpig‚Äô in one sentence seems to have evaporated. the #metoo gang is not up in arms anymore, common sense having prevailed. they were shown clips of kungfu panda and told that there are both male and female pigs. 
those who still harboured reservations were advised to look up the chinese calendar. maybe the issue needs to be on the agenda of the ongoing trade talks. it did take some american votes to get trump elected.

that was the us and the global waming president. the moral is if you‚Äôre a tweeting president, don‚Äôt make spelling errors, especially if the media and talkshow hosts have no better content.

text:
the reveal! seventeen year-old karishma sees herself after indu spent two hours doing her hair and makeup for a school function. celebrations are a reason to borrow everything from a sari to costume jewellery from neighbours and family. indu woke at 4 am to remake the borrowed choli (sari blouse) to fit, and sew a row of gold trim along the 8 metres of sari fabric. while the children crowded into the tuition center (indu's one-room home) to do their homework at 9 am, indu and karishma sat in the middle and managed to do hair, make-up, and check spelling for the kids. dwp is proud and happy to pay karishma's full tuition. her mom was widowed 14 years ago when she was four months pregnant with karishma's sister. she's a proud, hard-working cleaner at an office building, and a cheerleader for her four beautiful daughters. the oldest daughters work to help their mother pay the rent on their tiny slum home. a beautiful, happy, resilient family of strong women.

i had to purchase a new tv, get a new table, and get a new remote.  my dog was in the room barking his lungs out, because he sensed danger but could not do anything. 
if you need help, or just would like someone to talk to, give me a call, or email.  you are not in the alone.  you don‚Äôt have to stay silent.

love does not hurt.  if you are frightened from what someone might do, it is time to go!!!!!!

text:
kalpana chawla (march 17, 1962 ‚Äì february 1, 2003) was an american astronaut, engineer and the first female of indian origin to go to space.
she first flew on space shuttle columbia in 1997 as a mission specialist and primary robotic arm operator.
in 2003, chawla was one of the seven crew members who died in the space shuttle columbia disaster when the spacecraft disintegrated during its re-entry into the earth's atmosphere.
chawla was posthumously awarded the congressional space medal of honor, and several streets, universities and institutions have been named in her honor.
after getting a bachelor of engineering degree in aeronautical engineering from punjab engineering college, india, she moved to the united states in 1982 and obtained a master of science degree in aerospace engineering from the university of texas at arlington in 1984.
74th street in jackson heights, queens, new york city has been renamed "kalpana chawla way" in her honor.
nasa has dedicated a supercomputer to chawla.

text:
there is definitely a stigma surrounding any mental illness. we've been taught to stay quiet about the things that hurt us, about the situations that destroy us mentally. 
we're told that whatever happens in the home (or wherever else), once it makes you feel bad, you are not to talk too loudly about it. when are we going to wise up and realize that that is the kind of attitude and mindset that is destroying us as a people? we need to talk up. we need to seek out help. we need to know we're not alone. that is how we will really and truly heal, individually and as a nation. it's because of our constant silence that so many women and children are being brutally murdered! how long before we all realize that by outing our abusers we take back some of their power?

how? well speaking up means you are letting a woman in an abusive relationship know that she is not alone. it will help her to own up, stand up, and get out of that situation. let me paint a picture of what that means for us as a country:
üëâabuse rates decrease
üëâmurder rates decrease
üëâsuicide rates decrease
üëâwe'll have more women taking back control of their lives which means more productivity. healthier women mean children with a healthier mental state which means a more positive outlook for our future and economy. 
see the big picture here?ü§∑üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è so talk up people, encourage others to speak up, and most importantly listen. 
quick secret: i've been on antidepressants once and said they were vitamins. ü§´ ü§≠

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
an honor to be welcoming the #metoo movement founder tarana burke at the 2019 @torontoblackfilmfest on february 16, 9pm for a tribute & intimate talk.

she is one of time magazine's 100 most influential people in 2018, who will receive tbff 2019 social impact award during an intimate evening where she'll share her journey as women rights advocate.

this is exciting and quite a privilege to be moderating the discussion with her. .

tarana burke created the #metoo movement in 2006 in order to help young women of color who have survived sexual abuse. her movement has been instrumental in bringing sexual harassment and assault to the forefront today.

i couldn't be prouder to see people from all over the place reserving tickets to attend! .

spread the word and grab your #tickets now: www.torontoblackfilm.com  #tbff19 .
.
.

text:
standing out when you‚Äôre solo üßê
‚Ä¢
today at this beautiful stupa, the most important one in laos (it‚Äôs on all the currency here, and people make pilgrimages from all over the country to see it) i thought nothing could be brighter than this enormous golden place.
‚Ä¢
then two teenage lao girls ran up to me and motioned to their camera, and jumped in a selfie with me. their smiles were huge and genuine as they ran off with a perfectly pronounced ‚Äúthank you‚Äù. how cool it is to stand out sometimes, i thought happily to myself. there were plenty of other western tourists there, but i was the one they deemed selfie-worthy.
‚Ä¢
then later as i was walking around vientiene, which had felt very safe the day before, i could feel myself standing out in a different way. men on motorbikes turned around as they passed to leer at me, men in tuktuks made kissing noises as they passed me, men on the street visibly undressed me with their eyes. this was at 4 pm, not late at night. i actually had to check at one point to make sure i didn‚Äôt go out with my modest dress somehow hiked up or pulled down to accidentally expose myself: nope. just a maxi dress i‚Äôve worn many times before with no issues at all.
‚Ä¢
and then i wanted to stand out much less.
‚Ä¢
i abandoned my dinner plans and ate almonds at my hostel instead.
‚Ä¢
in my month in southeast asia so far, i‚Äôve experienced literally no street harassment until today. i‚Äôve only had a bunch of lovely people tell me what a wonderful smile i have, and it‚Äôs allowed me to let my guard down in a place where i‚Äôm very conspicuous for my height and my body and my skin and my eyes and my hair.
‚Ä¢
sometimes this makes me just want to hide inside, or go somewhere more familiar where i blend in more. (or punch every single one of those creepy dudes.) so tonight i‚Äôm staying in and watching gossip girl in bed before my flight to cambodia tomorrow.
‚Ä¢
but i‚Äôm also remembering those smiling girls this morning, and their pure hearts and joy. darkness, but also light.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green

text:
a tomar por culo is an expression used by our fellow spaniards that i particularly like ‚Ä¢ it means shove up the arse (whatever one wants to shove) ‚Ä¢ and it represents the feeling of one letting go, of setting one free, of doing whatever one feels is right, no matter what others think. it also refers to a place far far away. with all its meanings, a tomar por culo is what i want to say to all the women, men, girls and boys out there struggling. this too shall pass. we‚Äôll be fine. 
just love each other, use less plastic and eat less, mostly plants. 
everything else, a tomar por culo.

text:
sexual harassment is bullying or coercion of a sexual nature and the unwelcome or inappropriate promise of rewards in exchange for sexual favors. sexual harassment includes a range of actions from mild transgressions to sexual abuse or assault.

back in october 2017, women took to social media to share their experiences of sexual harassment. the #metoo movement went viral, spurring a national and global discussion on the issue.

an online survey launched in january by a nonprofit called stop street harassment offers some of that missing evidence. it found that 81 percent of women and 43 percent of men had experienced some form of sexual harassment during their lifetime. #iws #iws19 #iws2019 #indoreworldsummit #indoreworldsummit2019 #mun #modelunitednations #muniversiti

text:
can you see the scar on my arm? 
yes, that is the first scar of my self harm. i did it when i was in the 8th grade due to guilt. i was scared that i would be punished by the universe hence before the universe would punish me i punished myself..
then began the self harm.. i broke many promises... i hurt many people.. i made many mistakes.. it became an addiction.. it was a result of impulsivity..
and if you would have noticed i don't wax my arms. i like them how they are.  why is it that guys can have hair on their arms but girls shouldn't? i used to feel very embarrassed.. sometimes i still do when i don't wax my arms and wear a sleeveless or when i don't wax my legs and wear capris...
i have more scars in hidden places but the biggest and deepest are in my heart which i am trying to make disappear.. there is no bio oil or cream which helps.. trust me...
it's just time which will make things heal.. #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #metoo¬† #loneliness #pain #despair #prettygirls #perfectbody #hurtquotes #goodenough #positivevibes #honesty #realthoughts #mentalbreakdown #mentalhealthsupport #me #mentalillness #mentalhealthrecovery #mentalhealthmatters #mentaldisorder #bipolar #bipolardisorder #bipolardepression #bipolarawareness

text:
my love, you have been with me all this time. i have been holding your hand, kissing your forhead. i have held  you in my lap, wrapped you in my arms, in tormented nights. i have been singing a lullaby so sweet, it touches your cheek softly and wipes the tear that secretly leaves the corner of your eye. my love, i have never stopped being your worldly womb. i have kept you safe in my heart, where i exist. i have been there when you almost called out my name. i sat beside your bed, everytime you couldn't sleep. i played with your hair, when you imagined it. i was there when you thought you saw a glimpse of me. my love, i have always been there.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
domestic abuse in a relationship: recognise it
there are different kinds of abuse, but it‚Äôs always about having power and control over you.

if you answer yes to any of the following questions, you might be in an abusive relationship.

emotional abuse‚ùóÔ∏è does your partner ever:

belittle you, or put you down?
blame you for the abuse or arguments?
deny that abuse is happening, or play it down?
isolate you from your family and friends?
stop you going to college or work?
make unreasonable demands for your attention?
accuse you of flirting or having affairs?
tell you what to wear, who to see, where to go, and what to think?
control your money, or not give you enough to buy food or other essential things?

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

cnn

text:
it‚Äôs a good question. why start up a page on social media that is sure to stir up the trolls? and put you in a position to be abused and ridiculed? 
someone asked me that the other day and i have been thinking about why i am doing this. firstly last year here 69 woman were murdered by men. god only knows how many were raped, abused, harmed. this year alone there have already been 5 woman murdered. and we are only 6 weeks in. this in a country where you can‚Äôt just go and buy a gun. i don‚Äôt want to think about how bad it would be if we didn‚Äôt have gun controls here. 
the #metoo movement brought to light just how bad it is for woman out there. something most of us women already knew but hearing so many stories about what woman have been through was heart breaking. 
it‚Äôs because we can not walk down the street safely. we look behind us, hold our keys between our fingers, have several routes mapped out in our head. sometimes we just won‚Äôt go out alone anymore, it‚Äôs too unsafe. and we should be able to go out and come home safe. 
it‚Äôs because all around the world men in power are still trying to control our reproductive systems. it‚Äôs because we are still fighting the glass ceiling. it‚Äôs because it‚Äôs still not seen as ok for men to cry or have feelings or hurt. 
it‚Äôs because trans women can not go to the bathroom in peace. and woc suffer everyday in ways white people can not imagine, and sometimes refuse to believe. because woman who are disabled suffer physical and sexual abuse and often can not get help or get out of the situation. sometimes they can not verbalise what‚Äôs happening at all and suffer in silence, take the case of the woman in a coma who was raped and gave birth with no one having a clue, and this won‚Äôt be an isolated case. 
it‚Äôs because.... because things need to change. and i might be just one voice on the internet but i‚Äôm not the only one. when many people use their voice we become loud, eventually they, the people in power, the lawmakers, the police, eventually they will have to listen and things will change. and change will not  happen if we are quiet. 
so here i am putting myself out there as my soul sisters are to be heard.

hi guys...
d2d is calling on all creatives. here's your chance to earn monthly from your creativitivity!!! the winner of this contest walks away with #20,000, first runner up with #10,000 and the 2nd runner up with #5,000. do we have your attention now? to join in on this competition here's what to do;
1)the topic is; what do you think about nysc, noble service to the country or....?,create your unique content through dance, music, art whatever!! relating to this topic.
2)post your creation on instagram, facebook or twitter (in form of video or picture) with the hashtags #d2dyouthspeak and #d2dyouthspeaknysc
3)we will repost your entry on our page, tag as many friends to like and leave relevant comments on your reposted entry.
4)the most creative entry with the highest engagement wins.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
note: you must be using 2 hashtags, #d2dyouthspeaknysc and #d2dyouthspeak
tip: you can share your entry on all three social media platforms to increase your chances of winning. we will be checking all of them so the winners can be selected from any of the platforms.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
entries close on the 20th of february and winners will be announced on the 28th of february 2019

‚Ä¢
meryl streep's first nod came for best supporting actress in the deer hunter (1979). she lost out to maggie smith for california suite.
‚Ä¢
with 21 nominations under her belt and three wins ( kramer vs. kramer 1980, sophie's choice 1983 and the iron lady 2012), meryl streep is the most nominated actress in 91 years of academy award history.
‚Ä¢
she is up for best actress the year for the role of katharine graham on the post.
‚Ä¢
good luck meryl.

text:
we have a new staff pick! betraying big brother by leta hong fincher, journalist and guest speaker at this past year‚Äôs hong kong international literary festival. 
the three women featured on the front cover are li maizi, xiao meili, and wei tingting, photographed during a 2012 protest. li are wei are members of what lhf has dubbed the ‚Äòfeminist five‚Äô. want to learn more about this timely and informative book? we can help! jenny, our resident bookworm, has reviewed it for everyone, and we post her review here in its entirety (thanks jenny!): betraying big brother: the feminist awakening in china

leta hong fincher

this book is an excellent introduction to feminism in china today, and a lucid explanation of the significant challenges contemporary chinese women and men face as they work to make their country more equal and compassionate toward women and also the chinese lgbtq community. 
china‚Äôs society has modernized rapidly, but chinese women still struggle for everyday rights many women in the developed world take for granted, like equal access to public toilets and an end to sexual harassment on public transport. the book, which originally planned as an expanded inquiry into a group hong fincher has called the ‚Äúfeminist five‚Äù also tries to tell the chinese #metoo story, touching on women and lgbtq people who have chosen to speak out about harassment or assault. however, the preponderance of sexual harassment and assault in china and the near-absence of formal legal methods for combatting these problems makes the chinese case really different from elsewhere. 
this book is aimed at the interested non-specialist who knows little about contemporary chinese politics or society. however, even more knowledgeable readers will appreciate the detailed interview passages hong fincher includes in the book as well as her compassion for and solidarity with her interview subjects.

text:

text:
what an honor and pleasure to hear anita hill speak ! today i am once again reminded of how fortunate i am and have been to walk among the survivors _to be able to share my story and to have been blessed with the strength to not give up hope every single time i have been challenged . 
but how many of us have been able to do that ...i don‚Äôt know ! how many of my friends and colleagues have left school and their workplace because they felt simply powerless to fight back their perpetrators... i don‚Äôt know! how many of the children have been robbed of their childhood because of some awful, sick family members that took their sexual aggression out on them ... i don‚Äôt know! #metoo isn‚Äôt enough. in a world where one in 10 girls have experienced rape or sexual assault by the age of 20, and one in three women experience sexual or domestic violence during their lifetime, our current legal systems aren‚Äôt effective enough . we need to become more active and use our combined resources to take part in electing the right representatives, get involved in tackling legal and institutional discrimination, legal reforms and combating all forms of violence against women and girls . 
let us all be reminded that ‚Äúinjustice anywhere is a threat to justice everywhere.‚Äù what dr. martin luther king jr. said all those years ago still resonate with us today. because of women like christine blasey ford and anita hill whose painful experiences echo millions of unseen women that have been sexually assaulted and harassed, not only women but men are also calling out these (disgusting) men that deemed women as weak creatures, to be possessed, abused, denigrated and destroyed at their will. we need more men speaking up and calling out their perpetrators too! we need more men to stand together with us ! !we need our sons to grow up knowing what integrity is and living with dignity, honor and respect! 
please lend your voice and freedom to those that cannot find one yet . and remember, each of us is at fault when communities allow perpetrators to keep gaining power , survivors to go into hiding and systemic hate to fester. #endsexualviolence #lovewins #lendyourvoice

text:
‚ú®tarana j. burke‚ú®  is an¬†activist¬†who is best known for creating the me too movement which¬†raises awareness¬†about sexual harassment, assault, and abuse. tw: ‚ö†Ô∏è burke was born on september 12, 1973, in the bronx,¬†new york. she had many troubling experiences growing up in a low-income, working-class family. she was raped and sexually assaulted as a teenager. these incidents inspired burke to dedicate her life to improving the lives of girls going through similar hardships. in 1998, burke gave birth to her daughter, kaia, and raised her as a single parent.
burke‚Äôs career started in selma,¬†alabama¬†where she worked with the 21st century youth leadership movement, the black belt arts and cultural center, and the national voting rights museum & institute. in 2003, burke co-founded an african-centered rites of passage program for girls called jendayi aza. the program eventually evolved and in 2006 it became a¬†non-profit¬†called just be incorporated that focused on the well-being of young¬†women¬†of color. it was when she was working at this organization that burke first spoke the words ‚Äúme too‚Äù when trying to empathize with a young woman who was at the time being abused by her mother‚Äôs boyfriend. those words pushed her to work with and empower those who have endured sexual abuse. in 2008, burke worked at the art sanctuary philadelphia in¬†pennsylvania¬†and later served as a consultant for the 2014 oscar-nominated film¬†selma, which depicts the 1965¬†montgomeryvoting rights marches.
burke is currently the senior director at girls for gender equity located in brooklyn, new york which works to build the personal development skills of girls of color. burke also teaches empowerment workshops at schools and work places across the nation.

text:
thank you to @aidi_kansas for sharing her powerful abortion story. .
.
i was a poor 19 year-old art student on a scholarship when i found out i was pregnant. i had dropped out of high school in 10th-grade and began working to help ease the burden on my mother. what little money i made waiting tables went directly to help my mami, who worked 2-3 jobs to try to make ends meet. it was never enough.
.
.
like so many first-generation american latinas - i was raised in a strict, sexually oppressive household, where we were made subscribe to machismo, along with strong religious (catholic) convictions like marianismo. in my family‚Äôs eyes, only sluts and whores were sexual beings dumb enough to get pregnant outside of church-sanctioned marriage. the word abortion was never mentioned.  this is actually very typical in a latinx household. however - thanks to my white friends - i knew i didn‚Äôt have to become a hopeless statistic if i wanted something better for myself and my eventual children.
.
.
i never in my life felt so afraid and alone, yet i was determined to choose what was best for me and my future. it saddens me to think about how far i might have gone to make this pregnancy disappear from my life. thank goodness for roe v. wade. the most painful thing about my experience was not the actual procedure (although it was very painful), it was all the emotions i had to deal with the night before, during, and after the procedure that stayed with me. it was frustrating that on top of struggling with all my fears and doubts, my years of religious indoctrination also had me worrying that maybe i really was going to hell.  my partner at the time and best friend were the only ones who knew. so when we weren‚Äôt together i had to push my pain down and pretend like everything was fine. .
.
my mom passed away in 2009. i never told her. 
today - as a mother of a 16 year old son and a 12 year old daughter - my stance on abortion has only grown stronger. i‚Äôm so thankful that abortion care was available to me when i needed it, and i am determined to protect women‚Äôs reproductive rights.

text:
https://www.gofundme.com/alliesanfi
today is a big day for me. it marks one year since i was assaulted. 
it is a hard day for so many reasons. i am still so frustrated. i am still unable to work. the atrophy has left me unable to do the basic things i want to do. 
there is anxiety. fear. anger, because the person who did this to me has not been caught and probably will not. 
i think of all of the women and men who are going through this and i cry. 
i am lonely. i am scared.
but, i am not giving up. i will never give up. 
i give thanks to all of you who have made donations, made me hats, sent me clothing, provided me love and kindness, offered me support. i still need help. i still need things and i can't feel guilty for asking for that. i am very blessed for everything people have given to me - it means so much to me.
my love to all of you. 
#assault #recovery #pleaseshare #loveeachother #gfm #warrior #metoo #tw #victim #hurt #atrophy#warrior #trauma #unc #carrboro #chapelhill #nc #dtws

text:
in a moment of vulnerability during a very long wait for results on custody, this photo was snapped of my daughter and i. today, i won our custody hearing against my abusive ex. the last two days were the most emotional of my life as a court official psychologist evaluated our case. she listened to both sides, reviewed the evidence and spoke to our personal and professional witnesses. today, she concluded that the domestic abuse was real and mandated him to 6 months of therapy for anger management, coping and parental care. she also ordered supervised visitation until he shows he is working on himself via therapy. i won full custody and final say in all legal decisions.
for the first time, my terror and horror was validated by a non-biased party. for the first time, he was finally put in his place and told that he needs help for his actions and conduct. 
i cannot begin to explain the amount of relief that came over my heart. the dark cloud over my head shifted as the sunlight came through. tears of happiness were shed as my beautiful supportive friends and i celebrated a victory for women and children subjected to violence and abuse in silence. 
2018 was the hardest year of my life and now i can officially move on in my path to happiness and being the best mom i can possibly be. 
my attorney, therapist, friends and family are all the most amazing people and i am one of the fortunate people who had the support to get me through all of this. i am so grateful and humbled to have you all. 
to new beginnings 
#metoo

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text: why aren‚Äôt more people talking about how dangerous @facetuneapp is? especially how accessible it is to young girls. especially how influencers and celebrities use this to make young girls think they can achieve an unattainable image? in two taps of her fingers, natalie can make herself a size 0. you may recognize these two images from a couple weeks ago on @natateaaa‚Äôs instagram story. these stories blew up and had around 600 views (that‚Äôs a lot!) the first one is a real and unedited photo (other than a filter) and the second is edited with @facetuneapp. it‚Äôs so clear that being able to resize natalie‚Äòs body in under 15 seconds (13 to be exact) by pinching two places with a free app is heavily problematic. on this episode of blessed be the brains, natalie discusses the dangers of apps like facetune being so accessible and the history and future of the body positive movement. as always, link in bio ‚ú® you can also now listen on spotify! üß†‚ú®

text:
‚ö†Ô∏è trigger warning ‚ö†Ô∏è 3 years ago today i was left a shell of myself. marks on my body, heart and soul and i didn‚Äôt know how my life would ever be the same.  i didn‚Äôt know how i would heal from what was done to me and much less it being someone i thought i could trust. i blamed and hated myself for something that was not my fault. 
2 years ago today i was on edge, reliving horrible memories i wanted to forgot but were engrained even in my subconscious.  i ensured i was in a safe place and would feel safe knowing the day would be hard for me. 
1 year ago today i was still empty, searching for someone to give me the love i could only find in god. anxious, needy and codependent i never thought i could find myself again. 
today on the 3 year anniversary i look back on the pain. i look back on gods healing of my heart and soul that has happened and will continue to happen. i rejoice and praise god in having let go of my need for affirmation and dependence on others. today i empower women to get help immediately if they should ever find themself a victim of crimes like these. 
#metoo #metoomovement #threeyears #healing #survivor #godisgood #beauty #beautiful #blonde #blondie

text:
i saw this today.  women.  girls. that's what we do.
.
being female is hard, hard stuff most of the time. harder that than anyone who's not female can imagine.
.
between periods, cramps, gynecological exams, pregnancies, giving birth, raising children often with little or no help, harassment, unequal pay... stepping up and taking care of things in life no one else will do and taking on more than our fair share.
.
but women.  girls. when it gets rough, remember this.
.
we are powerful, we are stong, we are goddesses, we are goddess, we are the divine, we are life creators, we are makers, we are the mother, we are la luna, we are wisdom, we are magical.
.
we carry the the world.
.
we persist. always!
.
.
.
.
